state.label: a narrow, laminar parasphenoid ossification extends from near the anterior margin of the ethmoid plate along the ventral surface of the trabecula communis, expanding posteriorly to form a major portion of the floor of the cranial vault and joining a relatively well-ossified basioccipital

although the other cranial bones are not discretely formed, weak ossification is evident in the regions of the prootics, sphenotics, pterotics, epioccipitals, and at the edges of the exoccipitals surrounding the foramen magnum
comprises the hyomandibular, symplectic, quadrate, and a fully detached palatine
an irregular plate of cartilage with evidence of incipient ossification in some specimens

simple, posteriorly tapered rod lying along the anterior two-thirds of the dorsal margin of the symplectic; it is weakly ossified along most of its length and slightly expanded at its anterior tip where it articulates with the anguloarticular
no association with the remainder of the suspensorium; it is a short rod of cartilage extending from the anterior surface of the cartilaginous ethmoid plate to the maxilla
comprises a fully ossified dentary and anguloarticular, the latter articulating with the rod-like quadrate
tiny teeth are borne along the anterior third of the dorsal margin of the dentary
in the upper jaw the maxilla and premaxilla are fully ossified
bears tiny teeth along the entire length of its ventral margin
long and thin with some expansion distally
only the opercle is present. It is a small, oblong, laminar ossification that articulates anteriorly with a short posterior process of the cartilaginous hyomandibular
a single rod-like structure, weakly ossified perichondrally along its midlength, with the cartilaginous posterior end somewhat expanded

there are five branchiostegals, the larger anterior two articulating along the lateral surface of the ossified midlength of the ceratohyal, the smaller posterior three articulating with processes (the anteriormost process notably the largest) on the ventral margin of the expanded posterior cartilaginous area
there is a single lens-shaped cartilaginous hypohyal on the medial side of the anterior tip of the ceratohyal, articulating medially with the basihyal

at the posterior tip of the ceratohyal a short cartilaginous interhyal extends from the lateral side of the tip to the posteroventral comer of the hyomandibular, well posterior to the presumed hyomandibular-symplectic junction
the relatively large spatulate basihyal is broadly bifurcate anteriorly with a narrow rod-like posterior portion
first basibranchial is absent, and the second and third are represented by a continuous rod of cartilage articulating anteriorly with the basihyal
the cartilage that appears to represent the fourth basibranchial is continuous posteriorly with the cartilaginous anterior tips of the fourth ceratobranchials
rod-like bones, weakly ossified perichondrally along most of their length, each with a single row of tiny triangular teeth fused to the dorsolateral margin
slightly curved cartilaginous rods each with an ossified toothplate attached along the dorsomedial margin
a single triangular hypural plate is fused to the ventral margin of the upturned tip of the urostyle
seven principal rays articulate with the dorsal half, six with the ventral half. The dorsalmost and ventralmost principal rays are notably robust, being about twice as thick as the others
there are 5-7 procurrent caudal-fin rays both dorsally and ventrally
there are 15-22 bilaterally paired dorsal-fin soft rays (Watson, 1989, includes both species), all unbranched and unsegmented, and no spines

all dorsal-fin rays are supported by cartilaginous pterygiophores, each of which comprises a large proximal-middle radial and a small spherical distal radial (the latter obscured by fin-ray bases in Fig. 5)
there are 10-18 bilaterally paired anal-fin rays (Watson, 1989, includes both species), all unbranched and unsegmented
a simple splint-like bone with the ventral two-thirds of its length tightly adhered to the anterior margin of the coracoscapular cartilage; the cleithra do not meet at the ventral midline
the triangular coraco-scapular cartilage broadens ventrally and is fully continuous across the ventral midline with its contralateral member
(dorsal absent in all gobiids, both absent in some) absent
transparent body largely devoid of pigment
conspicuous ovoid swimbladder near midbody capped with pigment dorsally

char.label: Mature individuals of Schindleria possess well-developed sexually-dimorphic urogenital papillae similar to those seen in gobioids

A large frontal fontanel, in which there is no ossification, is divided into anterior and posterior portions by a transverse bridge of cartilage, the epiphyseal bar, that joins the taeniae marginales near their midlength
A large cylindrical block of cartilage, the maxillovomerine meniscus, lies between the rostral cartilage and the palatine
All elements of the gill arches except toothplates and ceratobranchials are cartilaginous
The fourth epibranchial is absent as are the interarcual cartilage, first and fourth pharyngobranchials, and fourth upper pharyngeal toothplate
The second pharyngobranchiallies directly anterior to, and is slightly larger than, the third
Each cartilaginous pharyngobranchial bears a toothplate along the ventromedial surface with teeth equivalent in size to those on the fifth ceratobranchials
The centra bear no parapophyses, ribs, or intermuscular bones
The anteriormost pterygiophores and rays of the dorsal fin are weakly developed
The first element is a single median structure and thus a true spine
There are 11-18 pectoral-fin rays (Watson, 1989, includes both species) borne along the rounded posterior margin of a large, paddle-like plate of cartilage, which may have two or three small foramina
The posttemporal is a small, obliquely oriented blade articulating anteriorly with the neurocranium and posteriorly with the cleithrum
Neural and haemal arches and spines of second and third preural centra
